[5] Cholera - India (Kerala), possible nosocomial spread
Date: Sat 28 Jun 2014
Source: The Hindu (edited)
http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/one-dies-of-cholera-in-palakkad/article6157873.ece


With the death of a 54-year-old woman who was undergoing treatment for cholera late Thursday night, 26 Jun 2014, the district administration and the Health Department have stepped up preventive measures in Alathur, Kuthanur and Chembukavu regions in the district [Palakkad district, Kerala state] from where 4 persons with symptoms of the water-borne disease had sought expert treatment at the Government Medical College in Thrissur.

The woman, from Kuthanur, succumbed to illness at the Thrissur Medical College on Thursday night, 26 Jun 2014, after 13 days of treatment for cholera. Her family members said she contracted the disease after she was admitted to a private hospital in Alathur following fever and vomiting. Her husband, who took care of her at the hospital, is now under treatment for cholera; 3 nurses of the hospital are also under treatment, they said. Health officials suspect that they may have been infected with the disease, possibly from consumption of contaminated water and food.

An expert team of doctors from Thrissur Medical College, under the supervision of additional professor Nileena Koshi, is camping in the area. More experts would reach there soon. They will investigate the reason for the sudden upsurge in cholera cases, apart from identifying short-term and long-term measures to prevent the disease. The district administration will conduct raids on canteens, hotels, and restaurants to ensure the quality of food. The authorities have appealed to the public to maintain personal hygiene while handling food and water.

Sanitation measures should be strengthened in all areas and local bodies should ensure that drinking water sources are not contaminated. Chlorination of wells and sprinkling of bleaching powder around water sources should be done periodically.

